a.xlink:title: The Alert class contains high level information about the event that triggered the alert.
The version of the IDMEF format in use by this alert.
Unique identifier for the alert.
Tenant ID to support multi-tenancy (e.g. decentralized infrastructure, local agency, subsidiary company, etc.).
The incident's category & subcategory as listed in [ENISA-RIST] using the format "category.subcategory" (e.g. "Attempt.Exploit").
Alert cause, if known at the time of detection.
Short free text human-readable description.
Expires 18 April 2023 [Page 28]
Severity of the alert.

A floating-point value between 0 and 1 indicating the analyzer's confidence in its own reliability of this particular detection, where 0 means that the detection is surely incorrect while 1 means there is no doubt about the detection made.
Free text human-readable additional note, possibly a longer description of the incident if is not already obvious.
Timestamp indicating the deduced start of the event.
Timestamp indicating the deduced end of the event.
Timestamp indicating when the message must be deleted.
Alternative identifiers; strings which help pair the event to internal systems' information (for example ticket IDs inside a request tracking systems).
Alternate categories from a reference other than [ENISA-RIST] (e.g. MISP, MITRE ATT@CK or another proprietary/ internal reference).
References to sources of information related to the alert and/or vulnerability, and specific to this alert.
Identifiers for the messages which were used as information sources to create this message, in case the message has been created based on correlation/analysis/deduction from other messages.
A list of IDMEF fields used to aggregate events. The values for these fields will be the same in all aggregated events.
A list containing the identifiers of previous messages which are obsoleted by this message.
A list containing the identifiers of other messages related to this message.
The Analyzer class describes the module that has analyzed the data captured by the sensors, identified an event of interest and decided to create an alert.
Analyzer IP address.
however still bear some meaningful sense.
Hostname of this analyzer.
brand and version).
Analyzer type.
Analyzer categories.
Type of data analyzed during the detection.
Detection method.
GPS coordinates for the analyzer.
Standard UN/Locode for the analyzer.
Internal name for the location of the analyzer.
The Sensor class describes the module that captured the data before sending it to an analyzer. The Sensor may be a subpart of the Analyzer.
The sensor's IP address.
however still bear some meaningful sense.
The sensor's hostname.
Expires 18 April 2023 [Page 37]
Standard UN/Locode for the sensor.
Internal name for the location of the sensor.
A string that describes the "capture zone" of the sensor, as a JSON-serialized string.
The Source class describes the source(s) of the event(s) leading up to the alert.
Source IP address.
Hostname of this source.
Free text human-readable additional note for this source.
Threat Intelligence data about the source.
User ID or login responsible for the alert.
Email address responsible for the alert.
Protocols related to connections from/to this source.
Source ports involved in the alert.
GPS coordinates for the source.
Standard UN/Locode for the source.
Internal name for the location of the source.
Identifiers for attachments related to this source.
Identifiers for observables related to this source.
The Target class describes the target(s) of the event(s) leading up to the alert.
Target IP address.
Hostname of this target.
Expires 18 April 2023 [Page 41]
Service or process impacted by the alert.
User ID or login targeted by the alert.
Email address targeted by the alert.
Target ports involved in the alert.
GPS coordinates for the target.
Standard UN/Locode for the target.
Internal name for the location of the target.
Identifiers for attachments related to this target.
Identifiers for observables related to this target.
The Vector class describes the vector(s) of the event(s) leading up to the alert. o Name, location, description, ...
Category for the detected "vector".
Name of the detected vector or "Unknown".
Rough estimate of the detected vector's size.
Free text human-readable additional note for this vector.
Expires 18 April 2023 [Page 45]
GPS coordinates for the vector.
Estimated radius around the provided geolocation in meters.
Standard UN/Locode for the vector.
Internal name for the location of the vector.
Identifiers for attachments related to this vector.
Identifiers for observables related to this vector.
The Observable class describes a feature or phenomenon that can be observed or measured for the purposes of detecting malicious behavior.
"Observable" attribute.
Name of the reference where the observable is specified.
Observable content.
The Attachment class contains additional data which was captured in relation with the event.
"Attachment" attribute.
Attachment filename.
A list of hash results for the attachment's Content.
Length of the content (in bytes).
References to sources of information related to the alert and/or vulnerability, and specific to this attachment.
If the attachment's content is available and/or recognizable from an external resource, this is the URI (usually a URL) to that resource.
Free text human-readable additional note for this attachment.
Internet Media Type of the attachment.
Content encoding.
The attachment's content, in case it is directly embedded inside the message.
